<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
	In the 'language' tags listed below, the 'value' attribute is a comma separated list of language codes, listed in preferred language order.

	Information on language codes can be found in these links:

		http://api.themoviedb.org/2.1/language-tags
		http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_ISO_639-1_codes
		http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1_alpha-2

	You can specify any number of language codes, but the results are limited to what's available on TMDb and not all languages are well populated.

	You can see what's available for a given movie by searching for it from here:

		http://www.themoviedb.org/movie
	

 	Special values
	==============

	Value			Meaning
	=====			=======
	"no language"  		Language neutral, e.g. a backdrop (aka fanart) image with no writing

	"language not set"	No language has been specified on the item in question e.g. a poster. 
								These items are likely to be in English, though no guarentee.


	Custom definition
	=================
	If you need to add another language, please do so from Media Companion, as although adding to the list below will work, your changes will be lost when you next upgrade.

	Example
	=======
	If your native language is Spanish, but you are fluent in Italian, then you might add a custom definition like this in Media Companion:

		Name  : Spanish\Italian
		Value : es,it,no language,en,language not set


	Missing your language?
	======================
	To get another language added to the list below, please create a new issue here:

		https://sourceforge.net/p/mediacompanion/tickets/

	In the description, include the language name & value. E.g.

		Name  : Greek
		Value : el,it,no language,en,language not set
 	
-->
